--------------------------------<br>
<br>
I don't think the lack of a UO2 makes the comparison that bad, other than whether or not it would be kept going at all. The fact is that many of the early adopters have upgraded, even if it's to a game from another company. Many others have come back because the newer games don't offer the same level of depth -- it will be interesting to see if this happens with EQ/EQ2. Once people burn through the initial release zones of EQ2, will they be tempted back to EQ by the fact that it has four (or five if they do another after POP and before EQ2) full expansions worth of zones and content? The initial zones in DAOC were not greatly smaller than original EQ, but to players used to a post Velius world, it looked pretty damned small.<br>
<br>
The 3d engine in UO is like the SOL engine, it's an upgrade to the existing one. It just uses 3d polygons to draw creatures rather than 2d sprites. It's not the one for UO2, which was to be a first person perspective full 3d like EQ, DAOC, AC, etc.<br>
<br>
As near as I can tell EQ2 = UO2 since the designer of UO is working on SWG and has brought a lot of his pet features to it, and EQ2 is branching off of SWG. If this is true, then EQ2 will be a really good game.<br>
<br>
There will be two others to watch for comparisons this year: Lineage2 and AC2. Lineage2 will be an upgrade like the planned UO-&gt;UO2 upgrade--a complete change in perspective from a very aging game. They claim they will have full support and development for Lineage 1 even after L2 release. AC2 from AC will be the one probably most similar to EQ to EQ2. I haven't heard what they plan to do for original AC, but from my point of view, of the major games, it's the one most in need of a full replacement.<br>
